_Personas transform abstract domain roles into tangible characters that developers, analysts, and stakeholders can actually understand. Think of them as your domain's field agents - each with their own mission brief, daily operational challenges, and success metrics. This guide shows you how to build personas that earn their place in your architecture._

---
## Start with the Right Roles

When building out your domain business architecture, start with the roles that are the key actors within the domain, plus the stakeholders that trigger the value stream(s) for that domain. As a Stealth EA, start by building out personas. For more information on personas read the book [[About Face - The Essentials of Interaction Design]].

Keep your persona to one page - constraint breeds clarity. This [[Stealth EA/Blog Entries/The power of a one page model|one-page]] deliverable becomes a central part of the overall design of the domain in question. It helps developers and other analysts understand a domain they may never have been a part of. Personas also become a foundation for test and training data, and inform training material development.

Since domain architecture is fundamentally about business architecture, start with the key roles that are unique to that domain. When actors within one domain are drawn from another domain, reference those existing personas rather than building new ones specifically for that domain.
## Understanding Daily Operations

In the course of a day, a domain role may support many value streams. The start and end of the day will be more about logistics and back office value streams. During the day they'll be more actively supporting customer-facing value streams. The creation of personas that trigger a domain's value streams will be more tightly coupled to a domain's value stream journey.

Creating a persona takes time, but maintaining a persona takes much more. Start with personas for the roles that have the greatest population within the organization. When creating archetypes, don't subdivide a given role into groups of less than 20-50 people.

_For example, don't create separate personas for "Junior Nurse," "Senior Nurse," and "Charge Nurse" if your organization only has 15 people in each role. Instead, create one "Emergency Department Nurse" persona and note the experience variations within the characteristics section._

Create consumer archetype personas only when you're building a specific channel or value stream experience for that user group.

> **Remember:** A useful persona shared today beats a perfect persona delivered next quarter. Start with the high-impact roles, validate with real people, and iterate based on feedback.

